{
"id": 4,
"title": "Greetings",
"description": "Learn how to greet others in Dholuo.",
"sections": [
  {
    "type": "theory",
    "title": "ðŸ“š Introducing Yourself",
    "content": {
      "introduction": "Greetings in Luo are quite formulaic and very important. The greeting you use depends on the time of day, and the familiarity between the people involved in the conversation.",
      "phrases": [
        {
            "dholuo": "Oyaore",
            "literal": "It (referring to the sky) has opened itself.",
            "english": "Good morning",
            "notes": "This greeting is used in the morning as the sun rises."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oyaore ahinya",
            "literal": "It has opened itself, verily", 
            "english": "Good morning",
            "notes": "This is how to respond when greeted with 'oyaore'. The word 'ahinya' means 'a lot' or 'verily'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Ichiew nade?",
            "literal": "You woke up, how?", 
            "english": "How did you wake up?",
            "notes": "The verb 'chiew' means 'to wake up'. And the question tag 'nade' means 'how'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Achiew maber",
            "english": "I woke up well"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oyaore uru",
            "literal": "It has opened up, y'all", 
            "english": "Good morning",
            "notes": "This is used when greeting multiple people at the same time. The 'uru' at the end translates to 'y'all'. The people being greeted would respond 'oyaore ahinya'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oimore",
            "literal": "It (referring to the sky) has covered itself.", 
            "english": "Good evening",
            "notes": "This greeting is used in the evening."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oimore uru",
            "literal": "It has covered itself, y'all", 
            "english": "Good evening",
            "notes": "This is used when greeting multiple people at the same time."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oimore ahinya",
            "literal": "It has covered itself, verily", 
            "english": "Good evening",
            "notes": "This is how to respond when greeted with 'oimore'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Iriyo nade?",
            "literal": "How did you pass your day?",
            "english": "How was your day?",
            "notes": "This greeting is used in the evening."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Ariyo maber",
            "literal": "I passed my day well.", 
            "english": "My day went well."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Idhi nade?",
            "literal": "You go how?", 
            "english": "How are you doing? (or how is the going?)",
            "notes": "This greeting can be used at any time of day. The word 'dhi' means 'to go'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Adhi maber",
            "literal": "I go well", 
            "english": "I'm doing good (or the going is good)"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Intie",
            "literal": "You are present?", 
            "english": "How are you?",
            "notes": "The verb 'tie' means 'to be present'. This greeting can be used any time of day"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Antie",
            "literal": "I am present", 
            "english": "I am fine."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Ingima?",
            "literal": "You are healthy?", 
            "english": "How are you?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Angima",
            "literal": "I am healthy", 
            "english": "I am fine."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Ere wach?",
            "literal": "Where is the news?", 
            "english": "What's up?",
            "notes": "'Ere' means 'where'. 'wach' means 'word' or 'news'. This person is asking, 'What's the word?' or 'What's up?'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Onge wach",
            "literal": "There is no word", 
            "english": "Nothing much",
            "notes": "This is how to respond when greeted with 'oyaore'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Manyien?",
            "literal": "what's new", 
            "english": "What's new?",
            "notes": ""
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Onge Manyien.",
            "english": "Nothing is new.",
            "notes": "You can also simply reply 'onge'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Ia kanye?",
            "literal": "You come from where?", 
            "english": "Where are you from?",
            "notes": "The verb 'a' means 'to come from'. Luos like to build familiarity by asking where a person is from."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Aa Seme.",
            "english": "I come from Seme."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oriti.",
            "literal": "May he (referring to God) protect you.", 
            "english": "Goodbye.",
            "notes": "The verb 'rito' means 'to protect'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Oriti ahinya",
            "english": "Goodbye.",
            "notes": "You respond to 'oriti' with 'oriti ahinya'."
          }
          
      ],
      "grammar_note": "Let's go over to the next section to see how these greetings play out in a conversation."
    }
  },
